Text messages notify users about COVID-19 exposures
  If you’ve been exposed to someone who has the novel coronavirus, a smartphone notification can make all the difference. But it also raises privacy and other potential concerns.
  As part of North Carolina officials’ contact tracing program, an automated text message went out to 173 iPhone users warning them that they’ve been exposed to someone who tested positive for COVID-19. The texts were sent out after state technicians and contractors attempted to call all the exposed individuals.
  Native Networks helped the North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services gather the contact information of everyone who has come into contact with people who tested positive. The Charlotte-based wireless carrier’s technology matched the data submitted by state health authorities to the pre-existing data it had about all of its customers’ phone numbers. The company then sent out automated texts — a more efficient system than contact tracers on the phone checking each day the patient’s symptoms, said Rich Miller, CEO of Native Networks.
  Miller has worked with public health departments in North Carolina and South Carolina on contact tracing since 2009. Since the pandemic started, his company has enabled four states — North Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia and West Virginia — to automate contact tracing have added automated text alerts.
  But the practice may also raise privacy and ethical concerns among those who have ever been in contact with an infected person, said Deborah Dobbins, a professor of epidemiology at Emory University near Atlanta.
  “How far into the community do we go?” said Deborah Dobbins, the school’s acting chair of epidemiology. “When do you say a public health decision has gone too far in exposing people’s information, and we should've kept it contract tracing and not mass exposes?”
